threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis:
The script begins by defining two variables: `exeUrl` which stores a URL pointing to an executable file, and `exePath` which defines the location where the executable will be saved in the temporary directory.

The script then uses PowerShell to download the executable from the specified URL and save it to the defined path. The PowerShell command is executed in a hidden window.

After a 10-second delay, the script assigns the temporary executable path to the variable `sbsssd`.

The script then attempts to bypass User Account Control (UAC) by adding registry keys. It adds a command to the `ms-settings\Shell\Open\command` key, setting its default value to the path of the downloaded executable. It also adds a `DelegateExecute` value to the same key with an empty string.

Next, the script starts the `fodhelper.exe` program, which is a Windows feature on demand helper, presumably to trigger the UAC bypass.

After a 3-second delay, the script deletes the registry key `HKCU\Software\Classes\ms-settings`.

Finally, the script exits.
